        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Phila. Oct. 17&#44; 1881<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. S. Morais&#44;<lb/>
                Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I return my thanks<lb/> for your kind reply of Oct. 4.<lb/></p> 
            <p>I have sometimes raised the<lb/> question whether &#91;Hebrew&#93; <hi rend="underline">may</hi> not<lb/> have been a word used for the yield<lb/> <hi rend="underline">in bulk</hi>&#8212;or <hi rend="underline">in gross</hi>&#59; perhaps as<lb/> we use the Eng. word <hi rend="underline">harvest</hi>&#44; some<lb/>times&#8212;as when we say &#34;Thy <hi rend="underline">harvest</hi> is<lb/> in the barn.&#34;  We should not speak of<lb/> &#34;a bushel of <hi rend="underline">harvest</hi>&#34; nor of eating<lb/> some <hi rend="underline">harvest</hi>.  Do you suppose that<lb/> after the Israelite had carried his tithes<lb/> to the sacred place&#44; and was about to<lb/> eat or consume them &#34;before the Lord&#44;&#34;<lb/> he would <hi rend="underline">then</hi> have spoken of drink&#44;<lb/>ing a cup of &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#63;  This is only a<lb/> question which has often arisen in<lb/> my mind.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>I am sickened by attempts to<lb/> promote a good cause by insisting<lb/> on what is false.  Dr Samson<lb/> has issued a supplement to his<lb/> Book&#8212;and he asserts that&#44; from time<lb/> immemorial&#44; the Jewish people have<lb/> used &#34;<hi rend="underline">unfermented wine</hi>&#34; in their<lb/> religious services&#44; marriages&#44; &#38;c.<lb/>  Now have you ever heard of a con&#45;<lb/>gregation which refused to use the<lb/> regularly sealed and certified wine&#44;<lb/> <hi rend="underline">on the ground</hi> that it was matured<lb/> by fermentation&#63;  Did my Jewish<lb/> people ever&#44; so far as you know&#44; ob&#44;<lb/>ject to the matured&#44; old wines&#8212;as<lb/> Madeira&#44; &#38;c &#38;c&#44; when made in such<lb/> way as to have suffered no desecration&#44;<lb/> and insist on having a substitute&#44;<lb/> as a raisin&#45;wine&#44; <hi rend="underline">for the reason</hi><lb/> that they desired a fluid in which<lb/> no <hi rend="underline">fermentation</hi> had taken place&#63;<lb/>  I should like to know whether&#44; at any<lb/> period&#44; this has occurred.  I stated&#44;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>last year&#44; in a Boston paper of<lb/> wide circulation and great influence&#44;<lb/> that I had been informed &#40;giving no<lb/> <hi rend="underline">names</hi>&#41; that the use of a raisin wine<lb/> was <hi rend="underline">not</hi> for the purpose of avoiding<lb/> fermentation&#44; but for other reasons&#44;<lb/> and that it was customary to allow<lb/> the raisin&#45;wine itself to ferment&#44; more<lb/> or less&#59; and that the regularly ma<lb/>tured wines&#44; when duly prepared and<lb/> certified&#44; were never refused for re&#45;<lb/>ligious services.  Was this statement<lb/> in any way erroneous&#63;  I am quite<lb/> desirous of being entirely <hi rend="underline">right</hi>&#44; and<lb/> then I can reply to pretenders&#44; with<lb/> a good Damascus weapon.  This<lb/> Samson is a pretender to great knowl&#44;<lb/>edge&#44; and one of our Reviews has men<lb/>tioned him&#44; by name&#44; as illustrating<lb/> the maxim&#45;&#45;&#34;A little knowledge is<lb/> a dangerous thing.&#34;  I have repeat<lb/>edly challenged his statements&#44; and<lb/> he has always observed silence.  In<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>this supplement he makes no at<lb/>tempt whatever to defend&#8212;and says<lb/> nothing about&#44; references which he<lb/> made to Jerome and other &#34;Fathers&#44;&#34;<lb/> in his volume&#44; although his decla<lb/>rations in regard to those writers<lb/> have been again and again pro<lb/>nounced utterly incorrect&#8212;i. e. in<lb/> the public journals&#8212;and pecuniary<lb/> offers have been made to <hi rend="underline">any one</hi><lb/> who would substantiate them&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I <hi rend="underline">suppose</hi> that his assertions in<lb/> regard to wines used in Hebrew<lb/> religious services are false&#59; and I<lb/> desire to have them properly met&#44;<lb/> if they are false.  I wish there&#44;<lb/>fore to know what is the practice<lb/> of your people in Europe&#44; and what<lb/> it has been &#34;from time immemorial&#44;&#34;<lb/> as Samson says.<lb/></p>
            <p>Excuse me for thus troubling you.<lb/>
                I am most respectfully<lb/>
                Yours <hi rend="underline">S. C. Brace</hi>&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>At the Mercantile Library.<lb/></p>
        </body>
